# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-systems-manager
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-systems-manager/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] CM applied over the lifecycle of a system provides visibility and control of its performance, functional, and physical attributes.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] CM verifies that a system performs as intended, and is documented in sufficient detail to support its projected life cycle.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] The CM process facilitates orderly management of system information and system changes for purposes such as to revise capability; improve performance, reliability, or maintainability; extend life; reduce costs; reduce risk and liability; or correct defects.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] The relatively minimal cost of implementing CM is returned manyfold in cost avoidance.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] The lack of CM (or its ineffectual implementation) can be very expensive and sometimes can have such catastrophic consequences such as failure of equipment or loss of life.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] CM emphasizes the functional relation between parts, subsystems, and systems for effectively controlling system change.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] It helps to verify that proposed changes are systematically considered to minimize adverse effects.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Changes to the system are proposed, evaluated, and implemented using a standardized, systematic approach that ensures consistency, and proposed changes are evaluated in terms of their anticipated impact on the entire system.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] CM verifies that changes are carried out as specified and that documentation of items and systems reflects their true configuration.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] A complete CM program includes provisions for the storing, tracking, and updating of all system information on a component, subsystem, and system basis.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] A structured CM program ensures that documentation (e.g., requirements, design, test, and acceptance documentation) for items is accurate and consistent with the actual physical design of the item.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] In many cases, without CM, the documentation exists but is not consistent with the item itself.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] For this reason, engineers, contractors, and management are frequently forced to develop documentation reflecting the actual status of the item before they can proceed with a change.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] This reverse engineering process is wasteful in terms of human and other resources and can be minimized or eliminated using CM.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Configuration management originated in the United States Department of Defense in the 1950s as a technical management discipline for hardware material items—and it is now a standard practice in virtually every industry.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] The CM process became its own technical discipline in the late 1960s when the DoD developed a series of military standards called the "480 series" (i.e., MIL-STD-480, MIL-STD-481 and MIL-STD-483) that were subsequently issued in the 1970s.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] This marked the beginning of what has now evolved into the most widely distributed and accepted standard on CM, ANSI–EIA–649–1998.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Many of these functions and models have redefined CM from its traditional holistic approach to technical management.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Some treat CM as being similar to a librarian activity and break out change control or change management as a separate or standalone discipline.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] CM is the practice of handling changes systematically so that a system maintains its integrity over time.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] CM implements the policies, procedures, techniques, and tools that manage, evaluate proposed changes, track change status, and maintain an inventory of system and support documents as the system changes.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] CM programs and plans provide technical and administrative direction to the development and implementation of the procedures, functions, services, tools, processes, and resources required to successfully develop and support a complex system.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] During system development, CM allows program management to track requirements throughout the life-cycle through acceptance and operations and maintenance.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] As changes inevitably occur in the requirements and design, they must be approved and documented, creating an accurate record of the system status.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Ideally the CM process is applied throughout the system life cycle.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Many professionals mix up or get confused with Asset management (AM, see also ISO/IEC 19770), where it inventories the assets on hand.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] The key difference between CM and AM is that the former does not manage the financial accounting aspect but the service that the system supports or in other words, that the latter (AM) is trying to realize value from an IT asset.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] The CM process for both hardware and software configuration items comprises five distinct disciplines as established in the MIL–HDBK–61A and in ANSI/EIA-649.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Members of an organization interested in applying a standard change-management process will employ these disciplines as policies and procedures for establishing baselines, manage and control change, and monitor and assess the effectiveness and correctness of progress.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] The IEEE 12207 process IEEE 12207.2 also has these activities and adds "Release management and delivery".
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Configuration Identification (CI): consists of setting and maintaining baselines, which define the system or subsystem architecture, components, and any developments at any point in time.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] It is the basis by which changes to any part of a system are identified, documented, and later tracked through design, development, testing, and final delivery.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] CI incrementally establishes and maintains the definitive current basis for Configuration Status Accounting (CSA) of a system and its configuration items (CIs) throughout their life cycle (development, production, deployment, and operational support) until disposal.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Configuration Control: includes the evaluation of all change-requests and change-proposals, and their subsequent approval or disapproval.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] It covers the process of controlling modifications to the system's design, hardware, firmware, software, and documentation.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Configuration Status Accounting: includes the process of recording and reporting configuration item descriptions (e.g., hardware, software, firmware, etc.) and all departures from the baseline during design and production.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] In the event of suspected problems, operators can quickly verify baseline configuration and approved modifications.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Configuration Verification and Audit: an independent review of hardware and software for the purpose of assessing compliance with established performance requirements, commercial and appropriate military standards, and functional, allocated, and product baselines.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Configuration audits verify that the system and subsystem configuration documentation complies with the functional and physical performance characteristics before acceptance into an architectural baseline.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] The software configuration management (SCM) process is looked upon by practitioners as the best solution to handling changes in software projects.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] It identifies the functional and physical attributes of software at various points in time, and performs systematic control of changes to the identified attributes for the purpose of maintaining software integrity and traceability throughout the software development life cycle.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] The SCM process further defines the need to trace changes, and the ability to verify that the final delivered software has all of the planned enhancements that are supposed to be included in the release.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] It identifies four procedures that must be defined for each software project to ensure that a sound SCM process is implemented.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] These terms and definitions can change somewhat from standard to standard.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] ITIL specifies the use of a configuration management system (CMS) or configuration management database (CMDB) as a means of achieving industry best practices for Configuration Management.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] CMS helps manage a federated collection of CMDBs.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] The benefits of a CMS/CMDB includes being able to perform functions like root cause analysis, impact analysis, change management, and current state assessment for future state strategy development.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] For information assurance, CM can be defined as the management of security features and assurances through control of changes made to hardware, software, firmware, documentation, test, test fixtures, and test documentation throughout the life cycle of an information system.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] For example, configuration requirements may be different for a network firewall that functions as part of an organization's Internet boundary versus one that functions as an internal local network firewall.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Configuration management is used to maintain an understanding of the status of complex assets with a view to maintaining the highest level of serviceability for the lowest cost.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Specifically, it aims to ensure that operations are not disrupted due to the asset (or parts of the asset) overrunning limits of planned lifespan or below quality levels.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] In the military, this type of activity is often classed as "mission readiness", and seeks to define which assets are available and for which type of mission; a classic example is whether aircraft on board an aircraft carrier are equipped with bombs for ground support or missiles for defense.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Configuration management can be used to maintain OS configuration files.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Many of these systems utilize Infrastructure as Code to define and maintain configuration.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] The Promise theory of configuration maintenance was developed by Mark Burgess, with a practical implementation on present day computer systems in the software CFEngine able to perform real time repair as well as preventive maintenance.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Understanding the "as is" state of an asset and its major components is an essential element in preventive maintenance as used in maintenance, repair, and overhaul and enterprise asset management systems.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Complex assets such as aircraft, ships, industrial machinery etc. depend on many different components being serviceable.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] This serviceability is often defined in terms of the amount of usage the component has had since it was new, since fitted, since repaired, the amount of use it has had over its life and several other limiting factors.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Understanding how near the end of their life each of these components is has been a major undertaking involving labor-intensive record keeping until recent developments in software.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Many types of component use electronic sensors to capture data which provides live condition monitoring.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] This data is analyzed on board or at a remote location by computer to evaluate its current serviceability and increasingly its likely future state using algorithms which predict potential future failures based on previous examples of failure through field experience and modeling.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] This is the basis for "predictive maintenance".
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Availability of accurate and timely data is essential in order for CM to provide operational value and a lack of this can often be a limiting factor.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Capturing and disseminating the operating data to the various support organizations is becoming an industry in itself.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] The consumers of this data have grown more numerous and complex with the growth of programs offered by original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] These are designed to offer operators guaranteed availability and make the picture more complex with the operator managing the asset but the OEM taking on the liability to ensure its serviceability.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] More recently configuration management has been applied to large construction projects which can often be very complex and have a huge number of details and changes that need to be documented.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] Construction agencies such as the Federal Highway Administration have used configuration management for their infrastructure projects.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] There are construction-based configuration management tools that aim to document change orders and RFIs in order to ensure a project stays on schedule and on budget.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] These programs can also store information to aid in the maintenance and modification of the infrastructure when it is completed.
[src:aws-systems-manager/configuration-management] This study yielded results indicating a benefit to using configuration management on projects of this nature.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] The concept of managing infrastructure through code emerged from early configuration management practices.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] In the 1990s, tools such as CFEngine, created by Mark Burgess in 1993, introduced the idea of describing system configuration in a declarative language rather than executing manual commands, laying the intellectual groundwork for IaC.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] IaC emerged as organizations began managing larger and more complex infrastructure, particularly with the growth of cloud computing and the need to provision resources consistently and at scale.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] Treating infrastructure configuration like software - storing it in version control, reviewing it, and deploying it automatically allowed teams to reduce manual errors and reproduce environments reliably.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] The ability to treat infrastructure as code and use the same tools as any other software project would allow developers to rapidly deploy applications.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] The value of IaC can be broken down into three measurable categories: cost, speed, and risk.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] Cost reduction aims at helping not only the enterprise financially, but also in terms of people and effort, meaning that by removing the manual component, organizations are able to refocus their efforts on other enterprise tasks.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] Infrastructure automation enables speed through faster execution when configuring your infrastructure and provides visibility to help other teams across the enterprise work quickly and more efficiently.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] Automation removes the risk associated with human error, like manual misconfiguration; removing this can decrease downtime and increase reliability.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] These outcomes and attributes help the enterprise move toward implementing a culture of DevOps: the combined work of development and operations.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] There are generally two approaches to IaC: declarative (functional) vs. imperative (procedural).
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] The difference between the declarative and the imperative approach is essentially *what* versus *how*.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] The declarative approach focuses on what the eventual target configuration should be; the imperative focuses on how the infrastructure is to be changed to meet this.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] The declarative approach defines the desired state and the system executes what needs to happen to achieve that desired state.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] Imperative defines specific commands that need to be executed in the appropriate order to end with the desired conclusion.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] Infrastructure as Code (IaC) allows organizations to manage servers and their configurations using code.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] There are two ways to apply these configurations to servers: the 'push' and 'pull' methods.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] In the 'push' method, the system controlling the configuration directly sends instructions to the server.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] In the 'pull' method, the server retrieves its own instructions from the controlling system.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] There are many tools that fulfill infrastructure automation capabilities and use IaC.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] Broadly speaking, any framework or tool that performs changes or configures infrastructure declaratively or imperatively based on a programmatic approach can be considered IaC.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] Traditionally, server (lifecycle) automation and configuration management tools were used to accomplish IaC.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] Now enterprises are also using continuous configuration automation tools or stand-alone IaC frameworks, such as Microsoft’s PowerShell DSC or AWS CloudFormation.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] All continuous configuration automation (CCA) tools can be thought of as extensions of traditional IaC frameworks.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] They leverage IaC to change, configure, and automate infrastructure, and they also provide visibility, efficiency, and flexibility in how infrastructure is managed.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] These additional attributes provide enterprise-level security and compliance.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] Community content is a key determinant of an open-source CCA tool's quality.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] According to Gartner, the value of CCA tools is "as dependent on user-community-contributed content and support as it is on the commercial maturity and performance of the automation tooling".
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] Established vendors such as Puppet and Chef have created their own communities.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] Chef has Chef Community Repository and Puppet has PuppetForge.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] Other vendors rely on adjacent communities and leverage other IaC frameworks such as PowerShell DSC.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] New vendors are emerging that are not content-driven, but model-driven with the intelligence in the product to deliver content.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] These visual, object-oriented systems work well for developers, but they are especially useful to production-oriented DevOps and operations constituents that value models versus scripting for content.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] As the field continues to develop and change, the community-based content will become ever more important to how IaC tools are used, unless they are model-driven and object-oriented.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] Other tools include AWS CloudFormation, cdist, StackStorm, Juju, and Step CI.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] IaC can be a key attribute of enabling best practices in DevOps.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] Developers become more involved in defining configuration and Ops teams get involved earlier in the development process.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] Tools that utilize IaC bring visibility to the state and configuration of servers and ultimately provide the visibility to users within the enterprise, which brings teams together to maximize their efforts.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] Automation in general aims to take the confusion and error-prone aspect of manual processes and make it more efficient, and productive.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] Allowing for better software and applications to be created with flexibility, less downtime, and an overall cost-effective way for the company.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] IaC is intended to reduce the complexity that kills efficiency out of manual configuration.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] Automation and collaboration are considered central points in DevOps; infrastructure automation tools are often included as components of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:aws-systems-manager/infrastructure-as-code] The 2020 Cloud Threat Report released by Unit 42 (the threat intelligence unit of cybersecurity provider Palo Alto Networks) identified around 200,000 potential vulnerabilities in infrastructure-as-code templates.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] A **patch** is data for modifying an existing software resource such as a program or a file, often to fix bugs and security vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] To *patch* is also the process of applying the data to the existing resource.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Patching a system involves applying a patch.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] A patch may be created to improve functionality, usability, or performance.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] A patch may be created manually, but commonly it is created via a tool that compares two versions of the resource and generates data that can be used to transform one to the other.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Typically, a patch needs to be applied to the specific version of the resource it is intended to modify, although there are exceptions.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Some patching tools can detect the version of the existing resource and apply the appropriate patch, even if it supports multiple versions.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] As more patches are released, their cumulative size can grow significantly, sometimes exceeding the size of the resource itself.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] To manage this, the number of supported versions may be limited, or a complete copy of the resource might be provided instead.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Patching allows for modifying a binary executable.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Although this can be technically challenging (requires a thorough understanding of the workings of the executable), it may be feasible when the source code is unavailable to build a full executable, and it allows for a smaller distribution which can be more economical than distributing full files.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Although often intended to fix problems, a patch can introduce new problems – a scenario called software regression.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] In some cases, an update intentionally disables functionality, for instance, by removing aspects for which the consumer is no longer licensed.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Patch management is a part of lifecycle management, and involves a strategy and planning of what patches should be applied to which systems and at what times.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Typically, a patch is applied in a permanent way (i.e. to storage), but in some cases, a patch is applied to memory (i.e. via a tool such as a debugger) in which case the change is lost when the resource is reloaded from storage.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Software update is sometimes conflated with patch even though they are not synonyms.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] An update can be implemented using patch files and the patching process.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Also, some may contend that patching is not limited to modifying file content – that adding, removing and replacing whole files is patching.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Typically, patch connotates a relatively small change, so a patch that is large in size or scope may be called the more general *software update* or another more specific name such as service pack.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Windows NT and its successors (including Windows 2000, Windows XP, Windows Vista and Windows 7) use *service pack*.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Historically, IBM used the terms *FixPak* and *Corrective Service Diskette* for such updates.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Historically, software suppliers distributed patches on paper tape or on punched cards, expecting the recipient to cut out the indicated part of the original tape (or deck), and patch in (hence the name) the replacement segment.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Later patch distributions used magnetic tape.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Then, after the invention of removable disk drives, patches came from the software developer via a disk or, later, CD-ROM via mail.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] With widely available Internet access, downloading patches from the developer's web site or through automated software updates became often available to the end-users.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Starting with Apple's Mac OS 9 and Microsoft's Windows ME, PC operating systems gained the ability to get automatic software updates via the Internet.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Computer programs can often coordinate patches to update a target program.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Automation simplifies the end-user's task, allowing them to only execute an update program, whereupon that program makes sure that updating the target takes place completely and correctly.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Service packs for Microsoft Windows NT and its successors and for many commercial software products adopt such automated strategies.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Some programs can update themselves via the Internet with very little or no intervention on the part of users.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] The maintenance of server software and of operating systems often takes place in this manner.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] In situations where system administrators control a number of computers, this sort of automation helps to maintain consistency.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] The application of security patches commonly occurs in this manner.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] With the advent of larger storage media and higher Internet bandwidth, it became common to replace entire files (or even all of a program's files) rather than modifying existing files, especially for smaller programs.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Patches for proprietary software are typically distributed as executable files instead of source code.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] When executed these files load a program into memory which manages the installation of the patch code into the target program(s) on disk.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Patches for other software are typically distributed as data files containing the patch code.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] These are read by a patch utility program which performs the installation.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] This utility modifies the target program's executable file—the program's machine code—typically by overwriting its bytes with bytes representing the new patch code.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] If the new code will fit in the space (number of bytes) occupied by the old code, it may be put in place by overwriting directly over the old code.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] If the new code is bigger than the old code, the patch utility will append load record(s) containing the new code to the object file of the target program being patched.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] When the patched program is run, execution is directed to the new code with branch instructions (jumps or calls) patched over the place in the old code where the new code is needed.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] On early 8-bit microcomputers, for example the Radio Shack TRS-80, the operating system includes a PATCH/CMD utility which accepts patch data from a text file and applies the fixes to the target program's executable binary file(s).
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] The patch code must have place(s) in memory to be executed at runtime.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Inline patches are no difficulty, but when additional memory space is needed the programmer must improvise.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Naturally if the patch programmer is the one who first created the code to be patched, this is easier.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Savvy programmers plan in advance for this need by reserving memory for later expansion, left unused when producing their final iteration.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Other programmers not involved with the original implementation, seeking to incorporate changes at a later time, must find or make space for any additional bytes needed.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] The most fortunate possible circumstance for this is when the routine to be patched is a distinct module.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] In this case the patch programmer need merely adjust the pointers or length indicators that signal to other system components the space occupied by the module; he is then free to populate this memory space with his expanded patch code.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] If the routine to be patched does not exist as a distinct memory module, the programmer must find ways to shrink the routine to make enough room for the expanded patch code.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Small in-memory machine code patches can be manually applied with the system debug utility, such as CP/M's DDT or MS-DOS's DEBUG debuggers.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Programmers working in interpreted BASIC often used the POKE command to alter the functionality of a system service routine or the interpreter itself.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] A patch for source code defines how to modify the text of code files.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Such a patch is usually a text file that encodes the differences between two versions of a file.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] As this type of patch is often created via the `diff` command, the patch file is also a diff file.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Source code patching is common for an open-source software project.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] Maintainers receive patches or people publish patches that fix problems and add functionality, like support for local languages outside the project's locale.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] In an example from the early development of the Linux kernel (noted for publishing its complete source code), Linus Torvalds, the original author, received hundreds of thousands of patches from many programmers to apply against his original version.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] The Apache HTTP Server originally evolved as a number of patches that Brian Behlendorf collated to improve NCSA HTTPd, hence a name that implies that it is a collection of patches ("a patchy server").
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] The FAQ on the project's official site states that the name 'Apache' was chosen from respect for the Native American Indian tribe of Apache.
[src:aws-systems-manager/patch-computing] However, the 'a patchy server' explanation was initially given on the project's website.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] In telecommunications, **provisioning** involves the process of preparing and equipping a network to allow it to provide new services to its users.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] In National Security/Emergency Preparedness telecommunications services, *"provisioning"* equates to *"initiation"* and includes altering the state of an existing priority service or capability.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] The concept of **network provisioning** or **service mediation**, mostly used in the telecommunication industry, refers to the provisioning of the customer's services to the network elements, which are various equipment connected in that network communication system.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] Generally in telephony provisioning this is accomplished with network management database table mappings.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] It requires the existence of networking equipment and depends on network planning and design.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] In a modern signal infrastructure employing information technology (IT) at all levels, there is no possible distinction between telecommunications services and "higher level" infrastructure.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] Accordingly, provisioning configures any required systems, provides users with access to data and technology resources, and refers to all enterprise-level information-resource management involved.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] As its core, the provisioning process monitors access rights and privileges to ensure the security of an enterprise's resources and user privacy.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] As a secondary responsibility, it ensures compliance and minimizes the vulnerability of systems to penetration and abuse.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] As a tertiary responsibility, it tries to reduce the amount of custom configuration using boot image control and other methods that radically reduce the number of different configurations involved.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] Discussion of provisioning often appears in the context of virtualization, orchestration, utility computing, cloud computing, and open-configuration concepts and projects.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] Once provisioning has taken place, the process of SysOpping ensures the maintenance of services to the expected standards.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] Provisioning thus refers only to the setup or startup part of the service operation, and SysOpping to the ongoing support.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] The services which are assigned to the customer in the customer relationship management (CRM) have to be provisioned on the network element which is enabling the service and allows the customer to actually use the service.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] The relation between a service configured in the CRM and a service on the network elements is not necessarily a one-to-one relationship; for example, services like Microsoft Media Server (mms://) can be enabled by more than one network element.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] During the provisioning, the service mediation device translates the service and the corresponding parameters of the service to one or more services/parameters on the network elements involved.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] The algorithm used to translate a system service into network services is called **provisioning logic**.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] Electronic invoice feeds from your carriers can be automatically downloaded directly into the core of the telecom expense management (TEM) software and it will immediately conduct an audit of each single line item charge all the way down to the User Support and Operations Center (USOC) level.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] The provisioning software will capture each circuit number provided by all of your carriers and if billing occurs outside of the contracted rate an exception rule will trigger a red flag and notify the pre-established staff member to review the billing error.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] Server provisioning is a set of actions to prepare a server with appropriate systems, data and software, and make it ready for network operation.
[src:aws-systems-manager/provisioning-technology] By auditing the system, you ensure OVAL compliance with limit vulnerability, ensure compliance, or install patches.
